Preheat your #oven to 200°C. Get the @sirloin steaks{2} out of your fridge (they will cook much better if not fridge cold). Chop the @sweet potato{1%large} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel!). Pop them on a lined #baking tray{} and drizzle over a splash of @oil{}. Season with @salt{} and the @chermoula spice mix{}. Toss to coat and roast on the top shelf of your oven until soft and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Pick the @mint leaves{} from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks). Pop into a #mixing bowl{} with the @cider & horseradish mustard{}. Finely chop the @parsley{}(stalks and all) and the @capers{}. Mix these into the bowl along with the @olive oil{} and a squeeze of @lemon juice{}. Keep to one side.

Halve the @baby plum tomatoes{} through the equator and pop into a large #bowl{}. Season with a generous pinch of @salt{} and stir in the @balsamic vinegar{}. Leave to one side.

> TIP: The salt will extract the juice from the tomatoes and make a lovely dressing for the salad.

Put your #frying pan{} on high heat. Drizzle a splash of @oil{} over the @sirloin steaks{} and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Rub the seasonings into the meat. When the pan is hot, carefully add the steak. If you like your steak medium rare like us, cook for ~{4%minutes} on each side. If you like it medium, add ~{2%minutes} cooking on each side. Once cooked, rest on your #chopping board{} for maximum juiciness!

While the steak rests, wash your frying pan, then return it to medium heat with a splash of @oil{}. Add the @baby spinach{}, stir and cook until it just begins to wilt, ~{1-2%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and get ready to serve.

Share the spinach between your plates. Mix the spicy sweet potato with the tomato and artistically arrange on your plates. Slice each steak into six even slices and arrange on top. Spoon your salsa across the steak. Enjoy!